03833nam a22004335i 9781503619036DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036190367 a10.1515/97815036190362doi  a(DE-B1597)582241  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0070002bisacsh1 aAnkersmit, F. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Representation /cF. R. Ankersmit. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. History and politics -- t1. History and Political Theory -- t2. Edmund Burke: Natural Right and History -- t3. Freud as the Last Natural Law Theorist -- tPart II. Democracy and History -- t4. On the Origin, Nature, and Future of Representative Democracy -- t5. Political Style: Schumann and Schiller -- tPart III. Democratic Theory -- t6. Democracy as Antifoundationalism -- t7. The Network, the Expert, and Representative Democracy -- t8. Compromise and Political Creativity -- t9. Respect -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis ambitious work aims to reintroduce history into political theory. Contemporary political philosophy—liberalism, communitarianism, and republicanism—disregards history because it is irrelevant to the nature of politics and to what constitutes a political problem. The author argues that this view reduces politics and political philosophy to a vapid academic game that is insensitive to both the essence and practice of politics. He proposes that an indissoluble link between history and politics lies in the notion of representation. Since history represents the past, and the core of democratic politics resides in political representation, the author sees representation as the common ground of history and politics. He welcomes, analyzes, and elaborates all the aestheticist connotations of representation. The history of Machiavellianism demonstrates how influential the impact of history has been on political thought, ironically resulting in the repression of history from philosophical reflection on the nature of politics. Historicist political philosophy is distinguished from its anti-historicist rival in terms of the distinction between historicist compromise and anti-historicist consensus, as seen in the work of Rawls and Rorty. Compromise is shown to be politically creative and open-minded, whereas consensus is conservative and totalitarian. Finally, the author argues that respect is the supreme democratic virtue, and that historicist political philosophy respects “respect,” while its anti-historicist rival has no rivals between disrespect and indifference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361903640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619036/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles